# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2023-dutch-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A referendum on the constitution of the Batavian Republic was held on August 8, 1797.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The draft constitution was rejected, eventually culminating in a coup d'état.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Following the French Revolution, the Patriots brought an end to the rule of stadtholder William V in the Dutch Republic, with support from the French army.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] They proclaimed the Batavian Republic, and established the National Assembly to draft a constitution, which would be put to a referendum.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Its members disagreed about the extent of suffrage and about whether to organise the republic as a federal or unitary state.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The Patriots had originally supported a federal state with autonomy for the provinces, but some wanted to emulate the unitary model of the French First Republic with a strong central government.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After two years of debate, a draft constitution with compromises was completed on May 10, 1797.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The draft constitution had been rejected by almost eighty percent, which meant that a new Constitution would have to be drafted.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] In the elections for the National Assembly a few months later, the supporters of a unitary state won the majority, but the supporters of a federal state retained the majority in the constitutional commission.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Meanwhile, in France, the radicals led by Pierre Augereau had seized power.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] With French help, the radical unitarists staged a coup d'état in January 1798.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A new draft constitution, establishing a unitary republic, was quickly adopted in the National Assembly.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The Constitution for the Batavian People was approved in a referendum on April 23, 1798.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic on 23 April 1798, approving the Constitution for the Batavian People.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] They proclaimed the Batavian Republic, and established the National Assembly to draft a constitution.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A compromised constitution was rejected by the electorate in an August 1797 referendum.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] On 22 January 1798, a coup d'état was carried out by those favouring a unitary state with the support of the French, who were dissatisfied with the referendum result and prolonged debates.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The remaining members of the National Assembly finished drafting the Constitution for the Batavian People two months later.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voters were asked on 21 April 1798 to approve the Constitution for the Batavian People.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] An overwhelming majority voted in favour, but only those who swore allegiance to the coup were allowed to vote.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After the referendum, another coup d'état was carried out by the Unitarians, and the constitution became effective in July 1798.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The French, who had a major influence on the Batavian Republic, were not satisfied with the 1798 constitution, so a new constitution was written, for which a referendum in 1801 was organized.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic on 6 October 1801.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After a previous referendum in 1798 resulted in a new constitution being approved, the French were not satisfied with this constitution, and under their influence a new constitution was written.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] In 1801, a referendum was held about the new constitution.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were counted as if they agreed to the new constitution, and the constitution passed with 87.46% in favour.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] On 16 October 1801, the new constitution became official.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic between 9 and 16 April 1805.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Although a new constitution had been approved in an 1801 referendums, the French authorities put pressure on the Batavian State Council to pass a new constitution in which executive power was held by a single person, the Grand pensionary, a post initially filled by Rutger Jan Schimmelpenninck.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution had 87 articles, which provided for a 19-seat Parliament with a three-year term which could pass or reject bills, but not change them.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voting was not secret and took place by signing registers at meetings, meaning invalid votes were not possible.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voters had the option to vote for, against or abstain, with abstentions counted as a "for" vote.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, the constitution was approved by 99.96% of voters.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 30 November and 4 December 1848.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] Held immediately after the Constitutional Reform of 1848, they were the first direct elections to the House of Representatives, and were the first to elect a States General to which government ministers would be responsible.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] Voting was restricted to men over the age of 23, and who paid a certain level of taxation.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] This limited the franchise to 55,728 people, roughly 11% of the male population over 23, or 2.5% of the total population of the country.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] Candidates were elected in districts in a two-round system; if no candidate received over 50% of the vote in the first round, the top two candidates would face a run-off.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] The districts had one MP for every 45,000 inhabitants.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1848-dutch-general-election] As there were no official political parties until 1879, all candidates were nominally independents.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1850-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 27 August 1850.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 17 May 1853.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] They followed the dissolution of the House of Representatives as a result of a government crisis caused by the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] The result of the elections was a defeat for Prime Minister Johan Rudolph Thorbecke and his liberals.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] Only the province of Groningen and Twente remained a liberal stronghold.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] The conservative Van Hall-Donker Curtius cabinet thus received ample support in the House of Representatives and Floris Adriaan van Hall became prime minister.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] However, the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy that had caused the government crisis was not reversed, although the Roman Catholic Church was restricted in its freedom of movement by the introduction of the Law on Church Societies.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] During the Constitutional Reform of 1848, the Catholic Church was allowed to determine ecclesiastical divisions within the Netherlands in the context of the separation of church and state.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] In 1853 this law was applied, and Pope Pius IX divided the Netherlands into five dioceses, including an archdiocese in Utrecht.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] Among the Dutch Protestants, there was much dislike of this action, which culminated in the April movement.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] The submission of the complaints by the April movement to King William III led to a crisis between the king and the Thorbecke I cabinet, which felt that the king had answered the April movement too positively and had not been sufficiently neutral.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] As a result, the cabinet resigned and the House of Representatives was dissolved.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/1853-dutch-general-election] According to the electoral law in force at the time, this was an exceptional situation: normally half the House was elected every two years, and not the House as a whole.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Early general elections were held in the Netherlands on 22 November 2023 to elect the members of the House of Representatives.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The elections had been expected to be held in 2025, but a snap election was called after the fourth Rutte cabinet collapsed on 7 July 2023 due to disagreements on immigration policy between the coalition parties.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The incumbent Prime Minister Mark Rutte announced that he would not lead his party into the election and that he would retire from politics.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] In what was described as "one of the biggest political upsets in Dutch politics since World War II", the right-wing populist Party for Freedom (PVV), led by Geert Wilders, won 37 seats in the 150-seat House of Representatives, becoming the largest party for the first time.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] All four parties of the incumbent coalition government suffered losses.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] After the election, a cabinet formation began to determine which parties would form the next government.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Subsequently on 16 May 2024, a coalition agreement was settled upon by PVV, VVD, NSC and BBB.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Immigration policy was heavily prioritised on the incoming government's agenda, as coalition representatives stated they would embrace the "strictest" asylum policy.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Numerous reforms were also expected across areas such as welfare and health, as emphasised by NSC leader Pieter Omtzigt during the election campaign, similar to addressing issues having surfaced in the aftermath of the Dutch childcare benefits scandal.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Several observers have described the new government as the most right-wing in recent history.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Following further negotiation amongst parties, Dick Schoof, an intelligence director, was then nominated for Prime Minister.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Shortly afterwards, all participating parties agreed to the nomination.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] He then became Prime Minister in a new cabinet formation over a month later on 2 July after being formally appointed by the King.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The 2021 general elections resulted in the formation of the fourth Rutte cabinet, consisting of a coalition of the People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD), Democrats 66 (D66), Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA) and the Christian Union (CU).
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Mark Rutte, leader of VVD, continued in his role as prime minister.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] After 2019, the government had the intention to limit the human impact on the nitrogen cycle.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] However, its nitrogen bill met resistance from several opposition parties, including the Farmer–Citizen Movement (BBB), which was founded in 2019 and entered the House of Representatives after winning one seat in the 2021 elections.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Its popularity grew quickly, and the BBB emerged as the largest party in the 2023 provincial elections, which also saw heavy losses for the ruling coalition.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] As the provincial councils indirectly elect the Senate, it meant that the ruling coalition would face more difficulty passing legislation.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The government resigned on 7 July 2023 after the four parties failed to agree on a proposed limitation of family reunification for refugees fleeing armed conflict.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The coalition government led by Mark Rutte collapsed ahead of the anticipated November elections due to irreconcilable disagreements on migration issues.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The dispute arose from Rutte's proposal to tighten restrictions on the reunification of asylum seekers' families, aiming to reduce the number of migrants following a previous scandal involving overcrowded migration centers.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] CDA supported Rutte's proposal, while the opposition of CU and D66 led to a breakdown in negotiations.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The parties decided unanimously that they could not remain together in the coalition.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The king asked that the prime minister and his government continue to carry out their duties in a caretaker capacity.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] This could have been seen as a move by Rutte to keep migration on the center stage as his party was disunited on his nitrogen policies.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] On 10 July 2023, Prime Minister Mark Rutte announced he would not run again as lead candidate for the VVD, and would leave politics when a new cabinet was sworn in.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Jesse Klaver announced that, although he wanted to continue as member of parliament, he would not be candidate for leader of the Labour Party–GroenLinks alliance.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Additionally, Vera Bergkamp, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, did not stand for reelection.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Pursuant to articles C.1, C.2 and C.3 of the electoral law, elections for the House of Representatives take place every four years in March, unless a snap election is called.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The 150 members of the House of Representatives are elected by open list proportional representation in a single nationwide constituency.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The number of seats per list is determined using the D'Hondt method.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] A list must receive a number of votes equal to or exceeding the Hare quota (1 full seat) in order to qualify for seat distribution, meaning there is an electoral threshold of 0.67%.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Voters have the option to cast a preferential vote.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The seats won by a list are first allocated to the candidates who, in preferential votes, have received at least 25% of the Hare quota (effectively ¼ of a seat or 0.17% of the total votes), regardless of their placement on the electoral list.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] If multiple candidates from a list pass this threshold, their ordering is determined based on the number of votes received.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Any remaining seats are allocated to candidates according to their position on the electoral list.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] In addition to the conventional debates, a series of debates between two or three party leaders were hosted by news program NOS op 3.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The debates are broadcast through the programme's media outlets, such as radio and YouTube.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The debates were broadcast in real-time and were held with a select group of young people present, who, in addition to the viewers on the YouTube live stream, asked the candidates various questions.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Thierry Baudet, founder and leader of the far-right Forum for Democracy (FvD) was attacked with an umbrella upon his arrival at Ghent University on 26 October 2023, resulting in a mild concussion.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] On 20 November, Baudet was beaten with a beer bottle at a campaign event in Groningen, and was later hospitalised.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Numerous politicians denounced the attack, with Mark Rutte stating that the attack was "totally unacceptable".
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The far-left group AFA Noord claimed responsibility for the attack.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] In the last polls before the election, NSC declined because it was unclear whether Pieter Omtzigt was willing to serve as prime minister should his party win the election.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Their voters mostly diverted to VVD and PVV.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Geert Wilders' PVV won 37 seats of the 150-seat parliament, more than doubling their seats from the previous election in 2021.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The left-leaning GroenLinks–PvdA (GL-PvdA) finished second with 25 seats.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The VVD party ended third with 24 seats.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] International media described the results as "one of the biggest political upsets in Dutch politics since World War II", and as a landslide victory for the Party for Freedom (PVV).
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Many analysts speculated that the rise of the PVV was due to great debate performances by Wilders in the weeks leading to the election.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] When migration became the largest issue of the election, it helped to boost the appeal of Wilders.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Some politics journalists opined that Wilders was able to build wider support by softening some of his statements after VVD leader Dilan Yeşilgöz suggested she might include the PVV in negotiations and declaring in a debate that he would be "a Prime Minister for all Dutch people".
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The Farmer–Citizen Movement saw a decline from their peak in the provincial elections in March, with many of their voters going towards NSC or PVV, for issues around nitrogen emissions were only a minor topic in the campaign.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The Dutch Parliamentary Election Study, a cooperation between 38 political scientists and sociologists, confirmed that migration was the largest concern amongst voters, resulting in the election win of issue owner PVV.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Furthermore, it concluded a third of the electorate had changed their favored party during the campaign, including across different ideological blocks.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The latter was partly caused by low trust in politics.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] According to the study, many voters – especially those voting for the PVV – favored a strong leader as a result of past political crises.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Following his party's performance, Wilders was praised by Hungary's Prime Minister, Viktor Orbán.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] He was also praised by far-right leaders across Europe such as Marine Le Pen, Matteo Salvini, André Ventura, Alice Weidel, Tom Van Grieken, and Santiago Abascal.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] All parties of the incumbent coalition government lost seats in this election.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Yeşilgöz denied her party's strategy was to blame for the PVV's success, saying: "It was not the VVD that made the PVV great.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] In February, Kim Putters (PvdA) was appointed informateur to determine the best structure for a new cabinet.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] He recommended forming an extra-parliamentary cabinet with PVV, VVD, NSC, and BBB.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Under the guidance of informateurs Elbert Dijkgraaf and Richard van Zwol, these parties reached an agreement on 15 May.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] Minister selection began on 23 May with formateur Van Zwol.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] On 28 May, civil servant Dick Schoof (independent) was nominated as Prime Minister after Ronald Plasterk withdrew over integrity concerns and other individuals refused.
[src:2023-dutch-general-election/2023-dutch-general-election] The 29 cabinet members were sworn in on 2 July.
